            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "@da-woods I found this issue after some searches. It would be nice if Cython could at least document this as a known/won't-fix issue.\n\nThis has a pretty profound impact on tab completion beyond Python's known issue (that `@property` has side effects), for all non-EOL'd Python versions (3.10+). If a cdef class has properties that could raise (as in our case where we want to raise exceptions to tell users that some features are not supported by the system), the tab completion on the entire class instance just does not work all together (see https://github.com/python/cpython/issues/88915 / https://github.com/python/cpython/pull/27401, for [bpo-44752](https://bugs.python.org/issue44752), which is being revisited in https://github.com/python/cpython/issues/112821). \n\nWe caught this issue during manual test (because no automation would find this, since no one would anticipate that tab completion could break and design any test to catch it) on the day we planned to release 1.0 (https://github.com/NVIDIA/cuda-python/issues/2053). After going back and forth with LLM and our in-house CPython/Cython experts, our current conclusion is to avoid using plain `@property` by aliasing it, so as to control how Cython emits code for us (https://github.com/NVIDIA/cuda-python/pull/2056). \n\nWhile this should definitely be fixed on the CPython side (and we're pushing for it: https://github.com/python/cpython/pull/149577), we also need to cover all non-EOL CPython versions, so any fix on the CPython side is unfortunately considered a slow (5+ yr) track by us. If Cython can fix it for us, it'd be a much better fast track. But if not, we'd hope that at least we could get blessing from Cython core devs for the aliasing approach (which is currently [tested here](https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/401b195debacf5e790c7d081d11e85025442eb16/tests/run/cdef_class_property_decorator_T264.pyx#L60)) 🙂 ",
